occurrenceRemarks: Multiple labels on this specimen. Hand written note indicates specie is 'shumardii Buckl '. This differs from original label that has specie as 'coccinea'. The leaves on this specimen are different from Quercus coccinea var. tuberculata in appearance. They appear as wide as they are high, symetrical sinuses and a much wider middle. Another later label agrees with original in classification and is the label 'Herbarium of the Morton Arboretum' Cited by Steyermark in Missouri Flora, p. 547. 1963. det. by W. Hess Oct. 18, 1988. Also it is noted on the specimen 'Quercus coccinea Munchh BHB 7/14/2011.

habitat: Ridge of resistance, orange fragile sandstone with a dry ridge community including Quercus falcata, Carya tomentosa, Quercus marilandica, Vaccineum arboreum, Pinus taeda, Pinus echinata (rare) and Pinus elliottii. Soil: light, fine-grained sand. Geology: Pliocene alluvial terrace. Leaves deep red, buds whitish tomentose at the tips. Small trees with straight trunks, bark dark and separated into small blocks at the base, with smooth, flat, broad ridges above and light grey above. 3 widely separated individuals were found and sampled at this site, all were 8-10 meters tall and ca. 5-10 cm. dbh. No fruits were seen.
locality: Franklinton; About 8.5 miles west of Franlinton limit along LA Hwy. 10; .5 miles west of Jct. LA HWY 62 above and just west of Witche Cr. at Sheridan.
